        "Answer": "[a] Wenceslao committed the following crimes: (1) the special complex crime of rape with homicide (2) theft and (3) unlawful possession of picklocks and similar tools under Art. 304, RPC. The rape and homicide constitute a special complex crime under Article 266-B, RPC. The theft is a separate crime because it was committed after the rape and homicide. The unlawful possession of picklocks is also a separate crime. [c] No, the answer will be different. If Loretta survived, Wenceslao would be liable for rape and attempted homicide (or frustrated homicide, depending on the gravity of the wounds), and theft. The rape and homicide would not complex into a special complex crime because there was no death."
