        "subject": "Criminal Law",
        "No": 418,
        "Question": "Porthos made a sudden turn on a dark street, and his Rolls-Royce SUV bumped the rear of a parked Cadillac Sedan inside which Aramis was then taking a nap. The impact awakened Aramis who, still groggy, alighted and saw Porthos also alighting from his SUV. Thinking that Porthos was about to attack him, Aramis drew his gun and shot Porthos in the chest. Porthos fell and was rushed to the hospital. He survived after a long confinement. (a) What are the kinds of unlawful aggression, and which kind was displayed in this case? Explain your answer.  (b) Standing trial for frustrated murder, Aramis pleaded self- defense. The Prosecution’s contention was that the plea of self- defense applied only to consummated killings. Rule, with explanations, on the tenability of Aramis’ claim of self-defense, and on the Prosecution’s contention.  (c) Porthos insisted that the element of treachery was present. To rule out treachery, Aramis asserted that both he and Porthos were then facing and confronting each other when he fired the shot. Rule, with reasons, on the respective contentions.  (2017 BAR EXAM)",
        "Answer": "(a) Unlawful aggression is of two kinds: (a) actual or material unlawful aggression; and (b) imminent unlawful aggression. Actual unlawful aggression is an attack or assault that is happening or is in progress. Imminent unlawful aggression is an attack that is about to happen. In this case, there is neither actual nor imminent unlawful aggression. Porthos was merely alighting from his vehicle, which does not constitute an attack. (b) The prosecution’s contention is not tenable. Self-defense can be invoked in frustrated or attempted homicide or murder. The stage of the felony does not affect the availability of self-defense. However, Aramis’ claim of self-defense is not tenable because there was no unlawful aggression on the part of Porthos. (c) There is no treachery as the attack was preceded by heated words. Treachery requires that the means of execution give the victim no opportunity to defend himself. Here, since both were facing each other, there was opportunity for defense, so treachery is absent."
